<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-06-28T12:24:10-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-06-28T12:24:10-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5350&amp;p=48375#p48375</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5350&amp;p=48375#p48375"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[After DMA Write I can see only 8 sprites.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5350&amp;p=48375#p48375"><![CDATA[
You can't have more than 8 in the same scanlines. It's impossible. In the same frame that is.<br /><br />If flickering really doesn't matter (and let me say that you will get a LOT of it with 17 sprites in a row) you should cycle the OAM slots they use every frame in order to cycle their priorities.<br /><br />Search for "sprite cycling" using the search function and you'll find a lot of stuff about it. Sprite cycling requires you to update the OAM every frame. The most common technique is picking one of the 64 slots at random to be your first, and then skip an odd number of slots for subsequent sprites.<br /><br />Say you started at slot 4. Use that and then skip 7 slots. that will place you at slot 11. Use that and skip 7 again. Now use slot 18 and skip 7 again. If you go past the last one the index will wrap back automatically, so don't worry.<br /><br />The result is that your sprites will appear to be randomly scattered across the OAM memory, and since they'll be scattered differently every frame, different ones will be selected to be displayed (but only 8 each frame, always), causing flickering.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Sun Jun 28, 2009 12:24 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
